"A patient says she needs a \"checkup.\" The chart shows an active pregnancy, a recent OB visit, and Medical Summary: \"RTO 3 weeks BPP w/MD.\" Her last Annual GYN was 15 months ago. What should control your next step?
Treat the documented RTO as the controlling instruction and build the BPP plus provider visit as the required paired workflow, clarifying with OB Portal only if the order cannot be built.
Correct: chart documentation outranks the caller's broad label. The documented BPP with MD controls the scheduling components.
A patient says she is newly pregnant. Her chart contains a New OB visit from two years ago, but no current prenatal sequence. She gives a reliable current LMP that places her at 6 weeks today. What is the correct interpretation?
Treat this as a new pregnancy, use the current reliable LMP, and build the New OB pair for when she will be in the normal 8–12-week window.
Correct: old pregnancy history is context only. Current reliable LMP starts the current New OB workflow.
A patient returns a missed nurse call after a Confirmation of Pregnancy visit. The note documents gestational age as 13 weeks 6 days and says the next step is prenatal care, but no exact appointment construction is recorded. What should you do?
Send a TE to OB Portal for approval and exact instructions before building the appointment, then follow the documented construction.
Correct: clearly out-of-window timing requires clinical approval rather than forcing the normal New OB schedule.
A patient at about 31 weeks wants to transfer prenatal care. She says she emailed records yesterday and asks you to confirm that the practice has accepted her. You cannot access the shared email inbox. What is the best response?
Document gestational age and outside-practice details, send a TE to OB Portal asking the clinical team to confirm record receipt and review acceptance, and explain that sending records does not guarantee acceptance.
Correct: gather the transfer facts, use the clinical review path, and avoid promising acceptance.
A non-pregnant patient reports non-emergency irregular periods. Her chart shows a Pap-only visit four months ago, a postpartum visit eight months ago, and her last completed in-department Annual GYN was 16 months ago. Which routine visit type is correct?
Annual GYN, with irregular periods included in the reason.
Correct: the last actual in-department Annual GYN is over one year old, so routine scheduling uses Annual GYN.
A patient has a positive home pregnancy test. She can name a date she thinks was her last period, but says her cycles are very irregular and she is not confident the date is accurate. What is the correct workflow?
Schedule a 15-minute provider Confirmation of Pregnancy and do not independently add a lab or sonogram.
Correct: unknown or unreliable LMP uses Confirmation first.
A patient at 34 weeks reports markedly decreased fetal movement since last night. In the same call, she asks for a prenatal-vitamin refill. How should the two requests be handled?
Escalate the decreased fetal movement immediately with a High Priority TE to OB Portal plus the urgent Intermedia channel, then handle the vitamin refill in its own separate refill TE.
Correct: prioritize the serious symptom and preserve clean issue ownership by separating the unrelated refill.
A patient says she miscarried over the weekend. The chart still shows a sonogram and OB visit next week. What is the navigator's correct classification and first action?
Treat it as a serious clinical report: create or update a High Priority TE to OB Portal, use the urgent channel, and await instructions before changing appointments or pregnancy status.
Correct: pregnancy loss requires urgent clinical review and the schedule remains unchanged until directed.
A patient calls back about the same refill that already has an open TE. During the call she also says she missed a glucose-test appointment and wants it rescheduled. What is the cleanest workflow?
Use Take Action on the open refill TE for the callback, and create a separate lab TE to OB Portal for the missed lab request; do not schedule the lab yourself.
Correct: same issue updates the existing TE, while the unrelated lab request gets its own routed TE.
A patient says, \"I only see Dr. Bank,\" but she is now reporting severe heavy bleeding. What is the best response?
Explain that the symptom must be escalated now, create a High Priority TE to OB Portal and use the urgent channel, offer another appropriate provider if clinically approved, and keep any Dr. Bank wait-list request separate.
Correct: serious-symptom escalation takes priority; preference does not delay care.
A pregnant patient says she was told to get an anatomy scan with Dr. Rosenberg. The chart shows a routine Anatomy order and no MFM referral or MFM appointment. Which path is correct?
Build the routine one-hour Anatomy scan with Dr. Rosenberg on the scan record and the separate provider visit required by the OB workflow.
Correct: the scan-provider field does not convert routine Anatomy into MFM care.
A patient says, \"The provider told me I need another growth ultrasound,\" but Medical Summary, the last note, and related TEs show no scan order. What do you do?
Explain that no supporting order is visible and send a clarification TE to OB Portal; schedule only after a documented order or clinical approval exists.
Correct: the chart must support the scan, and uncertainty is routed rather than guessed.
A reliable-LMP patient needs her New OB appointment. You find a 30-minute sonography block at 9:00, a provider New OB slot at 9:30, but the provider line is already triple booked at 9:30. What is the correct action?
Find another valid same-day back-to-back 30-minute sonogram-then-provider pair, confirm the provider line is appropriate, and mark the second appointment OB Verified.
Correct: all construction rules must be satisfied, not only the times.
Medical Summary says, \"RTO 2 weeks BPP w/MD.\" No same-provider pair is available in that window, but another OB provider can see the patient immediately after an available BPP slot. What is the best option?
Build the valid back-to-back BPP plus MD pair using the other appropriate OB provider, preserving the documented timing and components.
Correct: the workflow permits another appropriate OB provider when it creates a valid pair.
A patient calls at 10 weeks postpartum. She knows exactly which IUD she wants inserted at the postpartum visit, and the visit will be with Dr. Scott Stanislawski. Which construction is correct?
Book the 15-minute postpartum visit, document the required delivery details and IUD insertion intent, and do not add the usual post-insertion GYN Sono for this provider exception.
Correct: the later postpartum timing is acceptable, and Dr. Stanislawski is the no-post-insertion-sonogram exception.
A non-postpartum patient requests IUD insertion with Dr. Frieda Klein. Her last actual in-department Annual GYN was 18 months ago. Which appointment build is correct?
Book a 30-minute Annual GYN on the appropriate GYN template, followed immediately by GYN Sono, and mark the second appointment OB Verified.
Correct: annual is not current, Dr. Klein uses the 30-minute GYN workflow, and the provider-first pair ends with OB Verified.
A pregnant patient reports significant bleeding. An OB Urgent slot is visibly open in 40 minutes, but there is no nurse or provider approval in the chart, TE, or Teams. What should you do?
Create or update a High Priority TE to OB Portal, message the urgent Intermedia channel, and wait for clinical direction rather than independently booking the slot.
Correct: serious symptoms use the urgent escalation path; clinical staff decide the appointment.
A nurse gives written approval for an OB Urgent visit at 2:00 and says the patient also needs an OB URGENT SONO, but does not state whether the sonogram is before or after the provider. What is the safest action?
Book the approved OB Urgent, overbook if the written instruction requires it, and ask the clinical team to clarify the sonogram order before completing the back-to-back pair.
Correct: honor the written approval while clarifying the missing clinically directed sequence.
A patient sees an active lab order in her portal and asks you to book the lab for tomorrow. She also asks whether the result from last week was normal. What can the navigator do?
Create or update a TE to OB Portal covering the specific lab scheduling/order question and the result question, without booking or interpreting anything.
Correct: all OB/GYN lab appointment, order, missed-lab, and result questions go to OB Portal.
An outside office calls asking you to schedule a new MFM appointment for its patient. No referral or order from a Women's Health provider in your department is visible. What is the correct boundary?
Explain that MFM referral must come from a Women's Health provider in the department, do not schedule independently, and route the inquiry to Rebecca Wood for the MFM workflow.
Correct: MFM has a dedicated owner and a referral boundary.
A patient calls back with worsening severe pelvic pain about an open TE for the same issue. Which documentation is strongest?
Use Take Action on the existing TE with the worsening patient-reported facts, check High Priority, keep the correct OB Portal assignment, and send the urgent-channel message; keep the Reason concise, such as \"Severe Pelvic Pain.\"
Correct: update the same issue, use the system priority and urgent communication workflow, and document without diagnosing.
A patient calls about the same refill already documented in an open TE. The e-prescription log confirms the medication and prescribing provider, but she has changed pharmacies. What should you record?
Use Take Action on the open refill TE to add the new preferred pharmacy and callback details, retain the medication and prescriber context, and avoid promising approval or timing.
Correct: update the existing request with the changed actionable detail.
A patient says she will arrive 18 minutes late for a New OB pair at 10:00 and 10:30. What should the navigator send?
An Intermedia message with the patient account number, both appointment times, and expected lateness, then await the office decision without canceling, moving, or breaking the pair.
Correct: provide the required operational facts and leave the see/reschedule decision to the office.
A patient schedules a postpartum visit and wants to discuss IUD options but has not chosen a device. Which reason and appointment construction are complete?
Use the 15-minute postpartum template; document delivery date, infant weight, delivery type, delivering physician, and that the visit includes IUD discussion; do not add a sonogram.
Correct: complete postpartum documentation plus the discussion-only exception."

